qas.question: From the end of the 4th century, what territory was the western extent of modern-day Switzerland part of?
Where did the Alemanni settle in the 5th century?
Where did the Alemanni settle in the 8th century, forming Alemannia?
In the 8th century, what two kingdoms made up Modern-day Switzerland?
What Empire did the entire region of Modern-day Switzerland become part of in the 6th century?

context: In the Early Middle Ages, from the end of the 4th century, the western extent of modern-day Switzerland was part of the territory of <a0_0>the Kings of the Burgundians<a0_0/>. The Alemanni settled <a1_0>the Swiss plateau<a1_0/> in the 5th century and the <a2_0>valleys of the Alps<a2_0/> in the 8th century, forming Alemannia. Modern-day Switzerland was therefore then divided between the kingdoms of <a3_0>Alemannia and Burgundy<a3_0/>. The entire region became part of the expanding <a4_0>Frankish Empire<a4_0/> in the 6th century, following Clovis I's victory over the Alemanni at Tolbiac in 504 AD, and later Frankish domination of the Burgundians.
